<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-02-03T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-02-03T03:00:00-05:00" n="211" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d211">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/3931: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName corresp="#p_JNT1" type="from">Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-02-03T16:00:00+08:00">February 3, 1932—4
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 8:58 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>189. Legation’s 186, February 3, 1 p.m.<note n="38" xml:id="d211fn38">Not
                                printed.</note> Following from Harbin: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“February 3, 10 a.m. 1. Situation at and near Harbin
                                    unchanged.</p>
                                <p>2. Yesterday Japanese military demanded from the railway board 10
                                    trains to be used in transporting Japanese troops from Anganghsi
                                    to Harbin. Soviet side agreed but Chinese side refused despite
                                    open threats of Japanese military. Traffic on western line has
                                    been stopped presumably by Chinese military, leaving only
                                    eastern line open.</p>
                                <p>3. General <persName corresp="#p_LT2">Li Tu</persName> is now
                                    commander in chief of all organized Kirin troops.</p>
                                <p>4. <persName corresp="#p_OC1">Ohashi</persName> states that he
                                    has received a telegram from <persName corresp="#p_HLGS1">Honjo</persName> regretting that Japanese Army has been so
                                    slow in reaching Harbin.”</p></quote></p>
                        <closer>For the Minister:<lb/><signed><persName><hi rend="smallcaps">Perkins</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>